{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"286c4d49-8ca8-4be5-b92f-520b3086248e","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Here are the main authentication options:\n\n| Option | Flag |\n|---|---|\n| None (default) | `--auth None` |\n| Individual accounts | `--auth Individual` |\n| Microsoft identity platform (Azure AD) | `--auth SingleOrg` |\n| Multiple Azure AD orgs | `--auth MultiOrg` |\n| Windows auth | `--auth Windows` |\n\n**Quick start examples:**\n\n```bash\n# Basic API, no auth\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n\n# With Azure AD auth\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.onmicrosoft.com\n\n# With individual user accounts\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth Individual\n```\n\nYou can also add `--use-minimal-apis` for the minimal API style or `--use-controllers` for the traditional controller-based style.\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` for the full list of options.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4e91c54d-eb65-48b3-a8fa-bc72f5125713","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This seems like a general knowledge question about .NET (given the repository context with dotnet plugins). Let me answer from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase, as this is a general development question.","outputTokens":312,"requestId":"33C5:23056D:1F903A1:235B173:69E819F5"},"id":"8dc15bbe-a2d5-4a7c-861e-6adff35b03f6","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:44:45.109Z","parentId":"14025289-c325-4a83-b44d-47d0a20d6039"}
